<p>
<seg id=1> Representatives of the UN Global Climate Committee have continued their work in Buenos Aires, the capital city of Argentina. </seg>
<seg id=2> Meanwhile the American congress is arguing whether to approve the agreement drawn up in the Kyoto summit in Japan last year. </seg>
<seg id=3> Another report from Buenos Aires sent by Vlekus, a VOA correspondent, said that several American congressmen brought this dispute to the conference hall in Buenos Aires last Tuesday. </seg>
<seg id=4> Here are the details, Ma Kaiyue reporting. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> American democratic senators Ligoman and Rick announced last Tuesday in Buenos Aires that the Clinton administration would sign all agreements approved in the Kyoto summit. </seg>
<seg id=6> Both of the senators indicated that it would further persuade American representatives' if developing countries made promises on the issues of reducing global warming. </seg>
<seg id=7> In fact this was a necessary condition mentioned by the Senate's last few proposals. </seg>
<seg id=8> But certain American congressmen in Buenos Aires said they objected to any similar action made by the Clinton government. </seg>
<seg id=9> Samson Brunau, republican congressman from Wisconsin and chairman of the scientific committee, said the Kyoto agreement contained critical flaws, and would certainly be rejected by the American Senate. </seg>
<seg id=10> He said, </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Congressman Samson Brunau said, just as if the agreement had been put on one side, it is already dead before it reaches the American Senate, because the American Senate will not ratify it. </seg>
<seg id=12> The issue is what can we do now. </seg>
<seg id=13> To try to save it or just announce that the agreement has fatal defects and should be discussed again. </seg>
<seg id=14> Congressman Samson Brunau said, in both the Congress and the Senate there is no dispute between the parties. Some notable democratic congressmen also made similar comments. </seg>
<seg id=15> Klink, a Democratic Representative from Pennsylvania said he objects to the agreement because it will reduce the working opportunities and will damage America's industrial level. </seg>
<seg id=16> But Kuchinc, the Democratic Representative from Ohio, did not agree with him, and compared the fight with global warming with the struggle for world peace. </seg>
<seg id=17> He said the same decision would gain the Kyoto agreement a victory. </seg>
<seg id=18> He said, </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=19> Congressman Kuchinc said, I hope the process can last, and at the same time we should not ignore the tendency of working out a global settlement plan just because the temporary stubbornness of certain congressmen as to whether the American congress will participate or not. </seg>
<seg id=20> In the main summit hall in Buenos Aires, representatives are discussing on all kinds of issues, some of which must be left to the ministers of resources and environment of the 160 countries for settlement on Wednesday. </seg>
<seg id=21> The American representatives said, though some issues were put off until the next meeting by the American congress, this session made some progress. </seg>
</p>
